HOMEWORK 4

Note: All codes, plots and summaries are given at the end of the document. Note2: All data links are given in this RMD document. Files can also be found in my github master branch.

1 - For the first observation, Online News Popularity Dataset is used. You can achive the dataset from the following link: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Online+News+Popularity This dataset consists of 61 attributes and can be considered as regression dataset. From the codes below, you can see the testing results for all the methods. As a result, Lasso regression found to be the best as a classifying method. 2- To perform classification on categorical variables, Mushroom dataset (https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Mushroom) is used. In this dataset there are 22 attributes which shows a different attribute of a mushroom. Using those categorical values, classification tools are tried. For this dataset, SGB and RF methods had an error rate of 0, which indicates a perfect clustering. If we consider it to be true, they work as best. Also, with the DT methods, different minbucket sizes and cps are tried and an optimal value for the best fit is found.

3- Nextly, Diabetes data (https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Diabetes+130-US+hospitals+for+years+1999-2008) is examined.This data has 55 attributes which are mixed (consisting of both categorical and numeric data). For this method, different sized DT methods are tried and the lowest error rate is found in this method.

4- Lastly, default of credit card for clients dataset (https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/default+of+credit+card+clients) is observed. THis data set has a class imbalance problem, and the best fit is get with Lasso method.

GENERAL OBSERVATIONS:

  • Firstly, I observed that for regression datas, Lasso classification works best, which is expected. Since other methods are types of clustering, penalized regression works better.

  • For performance comparison, SGB is the slowest method. It performs a lot of iterations hence take a long time to get results. In clustering methods, Decision Trees works best since they do not interpret the whole data before seperation.

  • Looking at the cross-validation results, they are consistent with each method. This shows that all methods work as expected, and they can be chosen as to satisfy the need.

#random split
smpsize <- floor(0.8 * nrow(OnlineNewsPopularity))
set.seed(123)
train_ind <- sample(seq_len(nrow(OnlineNewsPopularity)), size = smpsize)
traindata <- OnlineNewsPopularity[train_ind,]
testdata <- OnlineNewsPopularity[-train_ind,]

Lasso <- cv.glmnet(as.matrix(traindata), as.matrix(traindata$shares), family = "gaussian")
predLasso <- predict(Lasso,as.matrix(testdata))
RMSELasso <- RMSE(testdata$shares,predLasso)

DTree <- rpart(shares~., data = traindata, method = "anova", minbucket = 5, cp = 0.005)
rpart.plot(DTree)

predDTree <- predict(DTree, testdata)
RMSEDT1 <- RMSE(testdata$shares, predDTree)

DTree <- rpart(shares~., data = traindata, method = "anova", minbucket = 4, cp = 0.005)
rpart.plot(DTree)

predDTree <- predict(DTree, testdata)
RMSEDT2 <-RMSE(testdata$shares, predDTree)

DTree <- rpart(shares~., data = traindata, method = "anova", minbucket = 4, cp = 0.01)
rpart.plot(DTree)

predDTree <- predict(DTree, testdata)
RMSEDT3 <-RMSE(testdata$shares, predDTree)

#Different values for minbucket and cp is tried. The best results (min MSE) is gathered with 
#bucket size 4 and cp 0.005. If we decrease cp too much, that results in very complex trees however
#error rates are high. Hence, the best results are gained with these params.

fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5, verboseIter = TRUE, classProbs = TRUE)
tunegrid <- expand.grid(.mtry=c(3,5,10), .splitrule = "variance", .min.node.size = 5)
RF <- train(shares~., data=traindata, method="ranger", trControl = fitControl, tuneGrid = tunegrid)

tunegrid <- expand.grid(alpha = 1,lambda = seq(0.001,0.1,by = 0.001))

newdata <- newdata[, sapply(newdata, nlevels) > 1]

smpsize3 <- floor(0.8 * nrow(newdata))
set.seed(123)
train_ind3 <- sample(seq_len(nrow(newdata)), size = smpsize3)
traindata3 <- newdata[train_ind3,]
testdata3 <- newdata[-train_ind3,]


fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5, verboseIter = TRUE, classProbs = TRUE)
tunegrid <- expand.grid(alpha = 1,lambda = seq(0.001,0.1,by = 0.001))
Lasso3 <- train(readmitted~., data=traindata3, method="glmnet", trControl = fitControl, tuneGrid = tunegrid)

smpsize4 <- floor(0.65 * nrow(newdata))
set.seed(123)
train_ind4 <- sample(seq_len(nrow(newdata)), size = smpsize4)
traindata4 <- newdata[train_ind4,]
testdata4 <- newdata[-train_ind4,]

Lasso4 <- cv.glmnet(as.matrix(traindata4), as.matrix(traindata4$DEFAULT_PAY), family = "gaussian")
predLasso4 <- predict(Lasso4,as.matrix(testdata4))
RMSELasso4 <- RMSE(testdata4$DEFAULT_PAY,predLasso4)

DTree4 <- rpart(DEFAULT_PAY~., data = traindata4, method = "anova", minbucket = 5, cp = 0.005)
rpart.plot(DTree4)

predDTree4 <- predict(DTree4, testdata4)
RMSEDT41 <- RMSE(testdata4$DEFAULT_PAY, predDTree4)

DTree4 <- rpart(DEFAULT_PAY~., data = traindata4, method = "anova", minbucket = 2, cp = 0.05)
rpart.plot(DTree4)

predDTree4 <- predict(DTree4, testdata4)
RMSEDT42 <- RMSE(testdata4$DEFAULT_PAY, predDTree4)

DTree4 <- rpart(DEFAULT_PAY~., data = traindata4, method = "anova", minbucket = 3 , cp = 0.001)
rpart.plot(DTree4)

predDTree4 <- predict(DTree4, testdata4)
RMSEDT43 <- RMSE(testdata4$DEFAULT_PAY, predDTree4)
#as we decrease the cp, our number of nodes(or size of the tree) gets larger. Hence RMSE value decreases
